aftsmen who traveled extensively in their search for challenging work, allowing for their influence to be felt across a broad region. Meinecke's unique approach to Islamic architecture will no doubt inspire others to emulate his approach in studying other regions or areas. Few, however, will be able to attain the consummate mastery of the subject which enlivens these essays.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIslamic architecture. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aClaster, Jill N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoucek, Priscilla P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311071692440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814763193.jpg  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK